42

I was referred to a cardiologist after my family doctor sent me for an EKG and found a right bundle branch block.

The cardiologist thinks the bundle branch block is hereditary and benign, but noticed that the "pressure was a little high in my lungs" -- which I  later figured out he was referring to pulomanory arterial arterial pressure...

He suggested a sleep study for sleep apnea, but I have very severe OCD and insomnia, so I figured the results might not be very helpful.  

I have a few questions:
- could hyperventilation cause a rise in pulmonary arterial pressure?
- can systemic high blood pressure affect pulmonary arterial pressure, and if so, can both be elevated by stress or lack of sleep?
- I jog 6 days a week (and have done so for 10 years, ever since losing a lot of weight) -- can jogging create this effect, and can taking a reading shortly after exertion affect pulmonary arterial pressure readings?

Thanks in advance!
